{
  "text": "Interestingly, GITRL expression is strongly increased during inflammation, mainly in APCs and endothelial cells. In response to proinflammatory stimuli, GITRL is rapidly upregulated (peak within 2-24 hours) and declines in 1-2 days to the initial or even lower levels [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . pDCs, stimulated with viruses, overexpress GITRL [CITATION_5] and human monocytes stimulated with staphylococcal enterotoxin B (SEB) become GITRL + [CITATION_6] . This is confirmed by in vivo experiment showing that 24-48 h subsequent to ocular herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) infection, GITRL expression is increased in APCs of draining lymph nodes [CITATION_7] . Not all pro-inflammatory stimuli promote GITRL ligand upregulation. For example, in endothelial cells, GITRL is upregulated by IFNα and IFNβ, and not by proinflammatory cytokines and LPS. In addition, T cells upregulate GITRL after activation [CITATION_8] or DEX treatment (Figure 1 ). In conclusion, the widespread distribution of GITRL, its expression in endothelial cells and the upregulation upon specific stimuli suggest that GITRL is involved in the development of inflammatory process.",
  "correct_citation": {
